    "content": "1st: B — 2nd: C — 3rd: A — Reason: Option B (Foreword + Translator's Preface) is strongest. A Foreword by an outside scholar lends credibility and situates the work within broader philosophical discourse for an English-language audience unfamiliar with it — someone who can say \"this is why this matters\" from a position of independent authority. The Translator's Preface is, in my view, non-negotiable: it's where we explain the terminological architecture (the 德 split, 现象X convention, 形而上/形而下 reinterpretation), justify our rendering choices, and provide the contextual scaffolding that English readers need to engage with the argument on its own terms. Option C (Translator's Preface only) is a perfectly viable fallback — the Translator's Preface does the essential work, and a Foreword is a \"nice to have\" rather than a structural necessity. Option A (Foreword only) is weakest because it leaves readers without the translation apparatus, and no outside scholar can substitute for the translators explaining their own decisions."
